    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-07-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-07-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="31"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d31">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/10</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Austro-Hungarian Ambassador</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_DCT1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dumba</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Austro-Hungarian Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Manchester, Massachusetts</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-07-26">
                        <hi rend="italic">July 26, 1914</hi>.</date>
                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received July 28</hi>.] </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Translation]</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">No. 178/res.]</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: In continuation of my note No. 171/res. of
                    July 24, I have the honor by direction of my Government most respectfully to
                    make to your excellency the following communication.</p>
                <pb facs="0332" n="18" xml:id="pg_18"/>
                <p>The answer of the Royal Servian Government to the Imperial and Royal Government’s
                    note is unsatisfactory. The Imperial and Royal Envoy at Belgrade thereupon
                    declared the diplomatic relations to be broken off and left the city of Belgrade
                    with the staff of the Legation. The Royal Servian Government is said to have
                    ordered the mobilization of the Servian Army as early as 3 p.m. of July 25.</p>
                <p>For our part the partial mobilization of the armed force was ordered.</p>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DCT1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">C. Dumba</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
